                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1768">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 816.00/148.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister to Guatemala</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-01-16T16:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 16, 1912—4 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>The Department learns from the Minister of Salvador that Guatemalan troops are
                    leaving the frontier in large numbers and that Salvador believes it unnecessary
                    to send two representatives to accompany the Military Attaché of your Legation
                    to the frontier.</p>
                <p>The Department, however, sees no objection to the Attaché going over the ground
                    if he could obtain reliable valuable information.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
